{"parse":{"title":"Hypsometric tints","pageid":8137228,"revid":817332817,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><div role=\"note\" class=\"hatnote navigation-not-searchable\">For a broader coverage of this topic, see <a href=\"/wiki/Terrain_cartography\" title=\"Terrain cartography\">Terrain cartography</a>.</div>\n<p><b>Hypsometric tints</b> (also called layer tinting, elevation tinting, elevation coloring, or hysometric coloring) are colors placed between <a href=\"/wiki/Contour_lines\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Contour lines\">contour lines</a> to indicate <a href=\"/wiki/Elevation\" title=\"Elevation\">elevation</a>. These tints are shown as bands of color in a graduated scheme or as a <a href=\"/wiki/Color_gradient\" title=\"Color gradient\">color ramp</a> applied to contour lines themselves. A typical scheme progresses from dark greens for lower elevations, up through yellows/browns and on to grays and white at the highest elevations. <sup id=\"cite_ref-hypo_tint_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-hypo_tint-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> Hypsometric tinting of maps and <a href=\"/wiki/Globe\" title=\"Globe\">globes</a> is often accompanied by a similar method of <a href=\"/wiki/Bathymetry\" title=\"Bathymetry\">bathymetric</a> tinting to convey depth of <a href=\"/wiki/Ocean\" title=\"Ocean\">oceans</a>; lighter shades of blue represent shallower water such as the <a href=\"/wiki/Continental_shelf\" title=\"Continental shelf\">continental shelf</a> and darker shades deeper regions.\n</p>\n<div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:HypsoTintedContours.pdf\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a1/HypsoTintedContours.pdf/page1-220px-HypsoTintedContours.pdf.jpg\" width=\"220\" height=\"142\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a1/HypsoTintedContours.pdf/page1-330px-HypsoTintedContours.pdf.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a1/HypsoTintedContours.pdf/page1-440px-HypsoTintedContours.pdf.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"2550\" data-file-height=\"1650\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:HypsoTintedContours.pdf\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>Hypsometric tinted contour lines</div></div></div>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#History\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">History</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Uses\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Uses</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"History\">History</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Hypsometric_tints&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: History\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>In his map of central <a href=\"/wiki/Italy\" title=\"Italy\">Italy</a>, c.1503, <a href=\"/wiki/Leonardo_da_Vinci\" title=\"Leonardo da Vinci\">Leonardo da Vinci</a> introduced the cartographic convention of using colored chalk to indicate changes in elevation.<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Rear_map.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/49/Rear_map.jpg/220px-Rear_map.jpg\" width=\"220\" height=\"162\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/49/Rear_map.jpg/330px-Rear_map.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/49/Rear_map.jpg/440px-Rear_map.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"2201\" data-file-height=\"1617\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Rear_map.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>First map of oceanic bathymetry, derived from <a href=\"/wiki/USS_Dolphin_(1836)\" title=\"USS Dolphin (1836)\">USS Dolphin (1836)</a> data</div></div></div>\n<p>Around the 1600s, the <a href=\"/wiki/Barometer\" title=\"Barometer\">barometer</a> was invented. For the first time, a scientific way of measuring elevations was possible. Francois Pasumot, became the first to develop a table to compare <a href=\"/wiki/Spot_height\" title=\"Spot height\">spot heights</a>. As a result, the <a href=\"/wiki/Interpolation\" title=\"Interpolation\">interpolation</a> of <a href=\"/wiki/Spot_height\" title=\"Spot height\">spot heights</a> to create <a href=\"/wiki/Contour_lines\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Contour lines\">contour lines</a> was successfully done in France, Germany and Denmark. In Austria the late 1820s, Franz von Hauslab was credited for the first colored contour maps using <a href=\"/wiki/Lithography\" title=\"Lithography\">lithography</a>. With the invention of <a href=\"/wiki/Chromolithography\" title=\"Chromolithography\">chromolithography</a>, copies of colored maps became more accessible. <sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>\nThe <a href=\"/wiki/Scotland\" title=\"Scotland\">Scottish</a> map firm <a href=\"/wiki/Collins_Bartholomew\" title=\"Collins Bartholomew\">John Bartholomew and Son</a> is credited with popularizing the colored <a href=\"/wiki/Contour_line\" title=\"Contour line\">contour line</a> technique, and their color scheme has become conventional: dark greens at low elevations, progressing through yellows and others, to browns and then grays and white at the highest elevations.\n</p><p>At right is \"The very earliest rendition of a bathymetric map of an oceanic basin. <a href=\"/wiki/Matthew_Fontaine_Maury\" title=\"Matthew Fontaine Maury\">Matthew Fontaine Maury</a> published this map in 1853 in <i>Explanations and Sailing Directions to Accompany the Wind and Current Charts</i>.\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Uses\">Uses</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Hypsometric_tints&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Uses\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Moon_worldwind.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3b/Moon_worldwind.jpg/220px-Moon_worldwind.jpg\" width=\"220\" height=\"163\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3b/Moon_worldwind.jpg/330px-Moon_worldwind.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3b/Moon_worldwind.jpg/440px-Moon_worldwind.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"1280\" data-file-height=\"948\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Moon_worldwind.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>The <a href=\"/wiki/Moon\" title=\"Moon\">Moon</a> with hypsometric tints of red for the highest points and purple for the lowest.</div></div></div>\n<div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Moon_Farside_LRO.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/04/Moon_Farside_LRO.jpg/220px-Moon_Farside_LRO.jpg\" width=\"220\" height=\"220\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/04/Moon_Farside_LRO.jpg/330px-Moon_Farside_LRO.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/04/Moon_Farside_LRO.jpg/440px-Moon_Farside_LRO.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"18000\" data-file-height=\"18000\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Moon_Farside_LRO.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>Compare the information available in this image of a slightly different face of the Moon to the <a href=\"/wiki/NASA_World_Wind\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"NASA World Wind\">WorldWind</a> depiction above.</div></div></div>\n<p>Similar to <a href=\"/wiki/False-color\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"False-color\">false-color</a> imagery, hypsometric tints can be used to make geographic information more accessible, as with this image of lunar topography.\n</p><p>Some cartographers have suggested that hypsometric tints are often used as decoration, rather than for informational purposes:<sup id=\"cite_ref-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<blockquote><p>&#8230;the current popularity of hypsometric tints has more to do with production ease and pretty colors than it does with our interest in elevation. &#8230; With hypsometric tints, the end result is often a map with pleasing colors that blend softly into one another in an orderly fashion, a design trait that people find attractive, even if they don\u2019t necessarily know or care about elevations.</p></blockquote>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Hypsometric_tints&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-hypo_tint-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-hypo_tint_1-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"> Buckley, Alileen. <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://blogs.esri.com/esri/arcgis/2008/05/09/hysometric-tinting/\">Hysometric tinting</a> \"ArcGIS Resource Center Blog\". Esri 9 May 2008. <small> Accessed 20 December 2017</small></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.royalcollection.org.uk/eGallery/object.asp?maker=12196&amp;object=912277&amp;row=436\">Royal Collection - A map of central Italy (Leonardo da Vinci)</a></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://thewalters.org/exhibitions/maps/image_pages/leonardo.html\">Claim of da Vinci's first use</a></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-4\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"> Patterson, Tom and Bernhard Jenny. \"The Development and Rationale of Cross-Blended Hypsometric Tints.\" Cartographic Perspectives, no. 69, May 2011, pp. 31-45. EBSCOhost, www.lib.byu.edu/cgi-bin/remoteauth.pl?url=<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external free\" href=\"http://search.ebscohost.com/login.aspx?direct=true&amp;db=aph&amp;AN=88157582&amp;site=ehost-live&amp;scope=site\">http://search.ebscohost.com/login.aspx?direct=true&amp;db=aph&amp;AN=88157582&amp;site=ehost-live&amp;scope=site</a>. <small> Accessed on 20 December 2017 </small> </span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-5\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-5\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://oceanexplorer.noaa.gov/library/readings/vicissitudes/media/gulf.html\">NOAA Ocean Explorer: First bathymetric map printed</a></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-6\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-6\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Tom_Patterson_(cartographer)&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1\" class=\"new\" title=\"Tom Patterson (cartographer) (page does not exist)\">Patterson, T</a>. and <a href=\"/wiki/Nathaniel_Vaughn_Kelso\" title=\"Nathaniel Vaughn Kelso\">Vaughn Kelso, K</a>. (2004). <i><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.shadedrelief.com/shelton/article/shelton.pdf#page=9\">Hal Shelton Revisited: Designing and Producing Natural-Color Maps with Satellite Land Cover Data</a></i>. <u>Cartographic Perspectives, 47</u>. p. 9</span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n\n<!-- \nNewPP limit report\nParsed by mw2172\nCached time: 20180918215905\nCache expiry: 1900800\nDynamic content: false\nCPU time usage: 0.048 seconds\nReal time usage: 0.092 seconds\nPreprocessor visited node count: 187/1000000\nPreprocessor generated node count: 0/1500000\nPost\u2010expand include size: 779/2097152 bytes\nTemplate argument size: 100/2097152 bytes\nHighest expansion depth: 7/40\nExpensive parser function count: 0/500\nUnstrip recursion depth: 0/20\nUnstrip post\u2010expand size: 3052/5000000 bytes\nNumber of Wikibase entities loaded: 0/400\nLua time usage: 0.005/10.000 seconds\nLua memory usage: 713 KB/50 MB\n-->\n<!--\nTransclusion expansion time report (%,ms,calls,template)\n100.00%   66.062      1 -total\n 51.98%   34.337      1 Template:Broader\n 49.74%   32.857      1 Template:Hatnote\n 41.95%   27.711      1 Template:Reflist\n 24.66%   16.292      1 Template:Format_link\n  7.22%    4.769      1 Template:Main_other\n-->\n\n<!-- Saved in parser cache with key enwiki:pcache:idhash:813